avva says:So, I did find one source of leak... but it's not the one that couldncause this bug, I think.nnLook at stats of some memcache process that's been running long. Innalmost all classes no. of items reported by 'stats items' is less thanntotal chunks of 'stats slabs' even though there aren't any freenslabs. Now the numbers aren't supposed to be equal, because some itemsnare out of linked list but tied up in delete queue or being printed.nBut if the difference is in thousands of items, e.g. here:nhttp://www.livejournal.com/admin/temp/memcache.bml?host=10.0.0.32:11212&mode=rawnsomething is wrong.nnAnyway, the bug I found is that when delete_handler() goes over thenqueue, it decreases refcount rather than call item_remove(). In almostnall cases it won't make any difference, because the item is still innthe linked list and item_remove() wouldn't free it anyway. But if:nn1) someone DELETEs an item and this sets its exptime to now()+4 andnputs it into the delete queue.n2) 4 seconds pass, but delete_handler() hasn't been called yet (it'sncalled every 5 seconds, approx.). In this brief and rare period ofntime, this item is called with GET.n3) since its exptime passed, the item is unlinked. Now whenndelete_handler() gets to it, it'll decrease the refcount, but noonenwill ever free it.nnnHe included a fix:nn--- cvs/wcmtools/memcached/memcached.c  Tue Jun 24 10:38:55 2003n+++ src/memcached/memcached.c   Tue Jun 24 16:50:01 2003n@@ -1058,7 +1058,7 @@n if (todelete[i]->exptime < now) {n /* no longer mark it deleted. it's now expired, same as dead */n todelete[i]->it_flags &= ~ITEM_DELETED;n-todelete[i]->refcount--;n+item_remove(todelete[i]);n } else {n todelete[j++] = todelete[i];n }nnnBut I think what I'm commiting will work just as well.  (it justnremoves items immediately instead of letting them fall off and dienlater)nnngit-svn-id: http://code.sixapart.com/svn/memcached/trunk@42 b0b603af-a30f-0410-a34e-baf09ae79d0bn

This makesnit so that memcached will error on a set when memory is full rather thanntossing an old item.nnThis is useful if you depend on items staying in the cache.nnJasonnnngit-svn-id: http://code.sixapart.com/svn/memcached/trunk@182 b0b603af-a30f-0410-a34e-baf09ae79d0bn

Use getrlimit and setrlimit to set limits for number of simultaneously open file descriptors. Get the current limits and try to raise them if they're not enough for the specified (or the default) setting of max connections.Do this before dropping root (if run as root) so we can raise the max limitnif needed.nnngit-svn-id: http://code.sixapart.com/svn/memcached/trunk@194 b0b603af-a30f-0410-a34e-baf09ae79d0bn

Add a new command line option: -r , to maximize core file limit. If the option is given, memcached tries to set the limit as high as possible, and at the very least to ensure it's non-zero, so *something* gets dumped. If it can't ensure that, memcached won't run.Also, when daemonising, the new option tells daemon() not to chdir tonthe root directory /, so that it won't try to create the core file there.nnngit-svn-id: http://code.sixapart.com/svn/memcached/trunk@197 b0b603af-a30f-0410-a34e-baf09ae79d0bn

new memcached tuning tool.  observe:lj@grimace:~$ memcached-tool.plnUsage: memcached-tool <host[:port]> [mode]nn   memcached-tool 10.0.0.5:11211 display# shows slabsn   memcached-tool 10.0.0.5:11211# same.  (default is display)n   memcached-tool 10.0.0.5:11211 move 7 9   # takes 1MB slab from class #7n# to class #9.nnYou can only move slabs around once memory is totally allocated, and onlynonce the target class is full.  (So you can't move from #6 to #9 and #7nto #9 at the same itme, since you'd have to wait for #9 to fill fromnthe first reassigned page)nnlj@grimace:~$ memcached-tool.pl 10.0.0.41:11211n  # Item_Size  Max_age  1MB_pages Full?n  6  64 B  12869 s  82 yesn  7 128 B  12446 s  74 yesn  8 256 B  11069 s  91 yesn  9 512 B  12184 s  54 yesn 10  1 kB  12120 s 106 yesn 11  2 kB  11498 s 181 yesn 12  4 kB  10087 s 189 yesn 13  8 kB   8322 s 124 yesn 14 16 kB   7335 s  69 yesn 15 32 kB   4591 s  31 yesn 16 64 kB   3378 s  17 yesn 17128 kB  39944 s   6 yesnnnlj@grimace:~$ memcached-tool.pl 10.0.0.41:11211 move 17 16nSuccess.nnlj@grimace:~$ memcached-tool.pl 10.0.0.41:11211 move 17 16nError: can't move from 17 to 16.  Destination not yet full?  See usage docs.nnlj@grimace:~$ memcached-tool.pl 10.0.0.41:11211n  # Item_Size  Max_age  1MB_pages Full?n  6  64 B  12687 s  82 yesn  7 128 B  12338 s  74 yesn  8 256 B  10968 s  91 yesn  9 512 B  11950 s  54 yesn 10  1 kB  11931 s 106 yesn 11  2 kB  11421 s 181 yesn 12  4 kB   9986 s 189 yesn 13  8 kB   8356 s 124 yesn 14 16 kB   7240 s  69 yesn 15 32 kB   4584 s  31 yesn 16 64 kB   3257 s  18  non 17128 kB  40287 s   5 yesnnngit-svn-id: http://code.sixapart.com/svn/memcached/trunk@212 b0b603af-a30f-0410-a34e-baf09ae79d0bn

patch from David Phillips <electrum@gmail.com>Here is a patch to configure.ac and Makefile.am to put the man page innthe correct location.  Trying to install the man page from ansubdirectory results in the subdirectory being used in the installnpath (it tries to install to doc/memcached.1).  This is the correctnthing to do:nn- create a Makefile.am in the doc directory that installs the man pagenwith man_MANSn- modify Makefile.am in the base directory to reference the docndirectory using SUBDIRSn- modify the AC_CONFIG_FILES macro in configure.ac to output the Makefile in docnnngit-svn-id: http://code.sixapart.com/svn/memcached/trunk@234 b0b603af-a30f-0410-a34e-baf09ae79d0bn

+2005-04-04 +   * patch from Don MacAskill <don@smugmug.com> 'flush_all' doesn't +   seem to work properly.  Basically, if you try to add a key which +   is present, but expired, the store fails but the old key is no +   longer expired.Subject: Serious bug in memcached - patch attachednParts/Attachments:n   1.1 Shown 44 lines  Textn   1.2 Shown 22 lines  Textn   1.3   OK  13 lines  Text (charset: UTF-8)n   23.2 KB Application, S/MIME Cryptographic Signaturen----------------------------------------nnn... or, at least, it seems that way.  :)  'flush_all' doesn't seem tonwork properly.  Basically, if you try to add a key which is present, butnexpired, the store fails but the old key is no longer expired.  Here'snoutput:nnget key1nENDnnadd key1 1 0 2n27nSTOREDnnget key1nVALUE key1 1 2n27nENDnnflush_allnOKnnadd key1 1 0 2n28nNOT_STOREDnnget key1nVALUE key1 1 2n27nENDnnI suppose it's possible there's some design reason why it behaves thatnway, but if so, I don't know what it is.  Certainly breaks our stuff.  :)nn(we built a memcached tracker which controls the state of our pool ofnmemcached processes.  It flushes any hosts/ports which fail at anynwrites, among other things, and this bug caused some big problems, asnyou can imagine).nnPatch against CVS attached.  It's probably mildly overkill (probablyndoesn't need to destroy the item on a stale 'get', only on 'add', butnit's pretty simple and gives me the warm fuzzies).nnDonnnngit-svn-id: http://code.sixapart.com/svn/memcached/trunk@236 b0b603af-a30f-0410-a34e-baf09ae79d0bn

fix some long-standing psuedo-bugs with regard to the delete-locked window (when you specify a time parameter to the delete command, which prevents adds/replaces for that many seconds)in particular, if you had a small timeout, less than 5 seconds, then anfuture add/replace which should've worked wouldn't because thendelete_timer wouldn't have run yet.nnthis has caused a lot of people just evalutating memcached and playingnaround as they read the protocol docs to go crazy, as they couldn'tnsee the delete timer happening, and it all just appeared random tonthemnnthis also unifies some duplicated code, and adds some assertions, innparticular in assoc_insert to make sure that key isn't already in thenhashtable.nnnngit-svn-id: http://code.sixapart.com/svn/memcached/trunk/server@337 b0b603af-a30f-0410-a34e-baf09ae79d0bn

Minor readability improvement: 1024 * 1024 instead of 1048576. Fix freesuffix corruption.When attempting to grow the freesuffix storage, the realloc is sizednto the number of bytes in freesuffixtotal instead of a number ofnpointers of that size.nnThat is, the original malloc is fornn  sizeof(char *) * freesuffixtotalnnbut the realloc for growth wasnn  freesuffixtotal * 2nnOn a 32-bit machine, this would have the effect of freeing half ofnthe freelist when an attempt was made to grow it.nnThe realloc is now consistent with the initial malloc.n

Return all errors for binary commands except not_found for getk.The theory is that we want quiet commands to be quiet in *normal*ncases.  A set that succeeds does not need to return anything.nnA quiet get has two normal cases:nn1) Got a value (must return it!)n2) not_found (quiet here)nnAll other errors are potentially interesting, so they will also benallowed through.nnClient authors can use this information to create bath commands ofnvarious types and not lose any useful status.  A multi-set can be asnefficient as a multi-get and still know which sets worked and whichnfailed (even in the case of CAS).n

fix a handful of socket listen bugs.AF_UNSPEC is still necessary for UDP sometimes.nWe guarantee that at least one address returned from getaddrinfo bindsnsuccessfully, and in cases of lacking network or ipv6 addresses some of thosensocket() calls might fail. dumb hack to self-repair stuck slabssince 1.2.6, most of the refcount leaks have been quashed.nI still get them in production, extremely rarely.nIt's possibly we'll have refcount leaks on and off even in the future.nnThis hack acknowledges this and exists since we want to guarantee, as much asnpossible, that memcached is a stable service. Fix for issue 72: 1.4.0 binary multi-get crash issueRepack the input buffer if the current command and key doesn't fit in theninput buffer (may occur if we read multiple commands in a pipeline)nn(Dustin's note):nnThe original test was connecting to localhost which was resolving ton::1 on a few machines. Clean up slab boundary checking.http://groups.google.com/group/memcached/browse_thread/thread/45b70cced2c4bd32nnIn items.c in memcached-1.2.8, these arrays allow indices up to butnnot including LARGEST_ID:nn...nstatic item *heads[LARGEST_ID];nstatic item *tails[LARGEST_ID];nnSo this comment (which appears twice) is confused:nn   /* always true, warns: assert(it->slabs_clsid <= LARGEST_ID); */nnThe assert should be checking for clsid < LARGEST_ID, not <=.  Andnthen the warning would go away.  Or was the intent always to have 256nentries in the arrays, not 255?nnSimilarly, this code in items.c should be checking >=, not >, asnheads[LARGEST_ID] would be out-of-bounds:nn   if (slabs_clsid > LARGEST_ID) return NULL;n   it = heads[slabs_clsid];nnIMHO the confusion stems from the fact that LARGEST_ID is not itself anvalid id, as the name seems to imply.n

Kill off redundant and incorrect sizing definition.It seems that in investigating the fencepost issue (issue59), it wasnrevealed that the 255 value of LARGEST_ID was well beyond what wasnever possible to be referenced.nnAs actual value was limited to the POWER_LARGEST definition innpractice, I have LARGEST_ID use POWER_LARGEST to define itself.n
Kill off redundant item_init.These are automatically initialized to 0 (both Trond and the spec saysnso, and I asserted it on all current builders at least once beforenkilling it off).n

Remove slab size special case for growth factor 2. bug56Using any growth factor, the minimum slab size is always 104 bytesn(unless using -n option to use a specific value) except for 2. In thisncase, it's 128 bytes and cannot be reduced using -n option (it can benincreased however).nnFrom slabs.c:n/* Factor of 2.0 means use the default memcached behavior */nif (factor == 2.0 && size < 128)nsize = 128;nnWhat I sugget is to simply remove this part. If the default behaviournneeds to be kept to 128 bytes per default when factor is 128, maybendefault value could for the -n option could be adapted to do so. But Indon't see a good reason for this specific difference between factor 2nand others.n

Update stat documentation to reflect allocation strategy.The documentation stated that memory allocation was always in chunksnof 1MB.  In practice, this gets less effecient as you get into largernslabs.nnThe 1MB thing (which can be controlled by -I) is both the maximum sizenand allocation unit so a single allocate event will attempt to get asnmany items for a particular slab as it can as long as the allocationnitself doesn't exceed the maximum item size.n

Add support for --enable-sasl-pwdb--enable-sasl-pwdb allows memcached to use it's own password file andnverify a plaintext password.nnThe file is specified with the environment variablenMEMCACHED_SASL_PWDB, and is a plain text file with the followingnsyntax:nnusername:passwordnnPlease note that you have to specify mech_list: plain in your saslnconfig file for this to work.nnEx:necho mech_list: plain > memcached.confnecho myname:mypass > /tmp/memcached-sasl-dbnexport MEMCACHED_SASL_PWDB=/tmp/memcached-sasl-dbnexport SASL_CONF_PATH=`pwd`/memcached.confn./memcached -S -vnnand you should be able to use your favorite memcached client with saslnsupport to connect to the server.nn(Please note that not all SASL implementations supportnSASL_CB_GETCONF, so you may have to install the sasl confign(memcached.conf) to the systemwide location)n

Fix type-punning issues exposed with GCC 4.5.1The errors below are due to pointer magic that isn't allowed if following Cnstrict-aliasing rules:nnmemcached.c: In function u00e2u0080u0098complete_incr_binu00e2u0080u0099:nmemcached.c:1023:16: error: dereferencing type-punned pointer will breaknstrict-aliasing rulesnmemcached.c:1044:13: error: dereferencing type-punned pointer will breaknstrict-aliasing rulesnmemcached.c:1061:17: error: dereferencing type-punned pointer will breaknstrict-aliasing rulesnnFix this by introducing a union type that allows access to the uint64_tnmember as necessary, but doesn't add any additional length to the structure.nThe size remains the same before and after; the only difference is explictncasts are now refactored into union member accesses and all compilers shouldnbe happy.nnSigned-off-by: Dan McGee <dan@archlinux.org>n

fix incr/decr race conditions for binary protthere were two race conditions in the incr/decr binary protocol handler. Onenwas the original fetches item outside of add_delta, and the second was innthe initializer.nnI went for the quick fix by changing the semantics of the store request to benan ADD instead of a SET, so if someone beat them in that very narrow race thenrequest simply bounces. fix race crash for accepting new connectionsInspired by a patch by Kazuki Ohta.nnSummary from a mail sent to the list by Shigeki:n[Example Scenario]n 1. throw alot clients (well over connection limit) to connect tonmemcached.n 2. memcached's file descriptors reaches maximum settingn 3. main thread calls accept_new_conns(false) to stop polling sfdn 4. main thread's event_base_loop stops accepting incoming requestn 5. main thread stops to acceess main_base at this pointn 6. a client disconnectsn 7. worker thread calls accept_new_conns(true) to start polling sfdn 8. accept_new_conns uses mutex to protect main_base's race conditionn 9. worker thread starts loop with listen_connn10. worker thread calls update_event with first connn11. after first update_event(), main thread start polling sfd andnstarts to access main_base <- PROBLEMn12. Worker thread continues to call update_event() with second connnnAt this point, worker thread and main thread both acccess and modifynmain_base.n---nnThe original patch coupled polling with the once-per-second clock timer. Mynpatch creates a 10ms poller which kicks off after the listener is disabled.nSwitching for a conditional would be too much rewiring for 1.4, as 1.6 solvesnthis in a better way.n

clean do_item_get logic a bit. fix race.the race here is absolutely insane:n- do_item_get and do_item_alloc call at the same time, against differentn  itemsn- do_item_get wins cache_lock lock race, returns item for internal testingn- do_item_alloc runs next, pulls item off of tail of a slab class which is then  same item as do_item_get just gotn- do_item_alloc sees refcount == 0 since do_item_get incrs it at the bottom,n  and starts messing with the itemn- do_item_get runs its tests and maybe even refcount++'s and returns the itemn- evil shit happens.nnThis race is much more likely to hit during the slab reallocation work, so I'mnfixing it even though it's almost impossible to cause.nnAlso cleaned up the logic so it's not testing the item for NULL more thannonce. Far fewer branches now, though I did not examine gcc's output to see ifnit is optimized differently.n

slab reassignmentAdds a slabs reassign src dst manual command, and a thread to safely processnslab moves in the background.nn- slab freelist is now a linked list, reusing the item structuren- is -o slab_reassign is enabled, an extra background thread is startedn- thread attempts to safely free up items when it's been told to move a pagen  from one slab to another.nn-o slab_automove is stubbed.nnThere are some limitations. Most notable is that you cannot repeatedly movenpages around without first having items use up the memory. Slabs with newlynassigned memory work off of a pointer, handing out chunks individually. Wenwould need to change that to quickly split chunks for all newly assigned pagesninto that slabs freelist.nnFurther testing is required to ensure such is possible without impactingnperformance.n

initial slab automoverEnable at startup with -o slab_reassign,slab_automovennEnable or disable at runtime with slabs automove 1rnnnHas many weaknesses. close some idiotic race conditionsdo_item_update could decide to update an item, then wait on the cache_lock,nbut the item could be unlinked in the meantime.nncaused this to happen on purpose by flooding with sets, then flushingnrepeatedly. flush has to unlink items until it hits the previous second.n

fix braindead linked list failI re-implemented a linked list for the slab freelist since we don't need tonmanage the tail, check the previous item, and use it as a FIFO. tests: loop on short binary packet readsAwesome bug goes like this:nnlet c1 be the commit of the good state and c2 be the commitnimmediately after (in a bad state).  t1 is the state of the tree in c1nand t2 is the state of the tree in c2nnIn their natural states, we have this:nnc1 -> t1 -> successnc1 -> t2 -> failnnHowever, if you takennc1 -> t1 -> patch to t2 -> successnc2 -> t2 -> patch to t1 -> failnnSo t1 *and* t2 both succeed if the committed tree is c1, but both fail ofnthe committed tree is c2.nnThe difference?  c1 has a tag that points to it so the version number isn1.2.10 whereas the version number for the unreleased c2 isn1.4.10-1-gee486ab -- a bit longer, breaks stuff in tests that try tonprint stats.n

pre-split slab pages into slab freelistsslab freelists used to be malloc'ed arrays. then they were changed into anfreelist. now we pre-split newly assigned/moved pages into a slabs freelistninstead of lazily pulling pointers as needed.nnThe loop is pretty darn direct and I can't measure a performance impact ofnthis relatively rare event.nnIn doing this, slab reassign can move memory without having to wait for anclass to chew through its recently assigned page first.n

remove end_page_ptr business from slabsslab memory assignment used to lazily split a new page into chunks as memorynwas requested. now it doesn't, so drop all the related code.nnCuts the memory assignment hotpath a tiny bit, so that's exciting.n

split slab rebalance and automove threadsslab rebalancer now chillaxes on a signal and waits a lot less time whennhitting a busy item. automove is its own thread now, and signals rebal whennnecessary.nnwhen entering the command slabs reassign 1 2 it should start moving anpage instantly.n

slab rebalancing from random classspecifying -1 as the src class for a slabs reassign will pick the firstnavailable, rolling through the list on each request (so as to not bias againstnthe smaller classes).nnSo if you're in a hurry and have to move memory into class 5, you may now mashnit without thinking.n

alloc loop now attempts an item_lockFixes a few issues with a restructuring... I think -M was broken before,nshould be fixed now. Add a stats conns command to show the states of open connections.This is mostly for debugging purposes, e.g., to detect hung clients,nbut the implementation also simplifies management of connectionndescriptors by eliminating use of the freelist and allocating anstatic pointer array indexed by descriptor. (The actual connnstructures are still allocated on demand, so the impact on memorynconsumption is negligible.)nnTo be able to show multiple concurrent UDP requests, the UDP socketnis dup()ed so that each worker thread has its own UDP file descriptornto process rather than all sharing a single one. This means thenserver can handle slightly fewer TCP clients before running upnagainst its file descriptor limit, but any installation that'snrunning that close to the limit really ought to either raise thenlimit or use a proxy of some kind anyway, so this should have nonreal-world downside.n

fix LRU contention for first minute of uptimeNoticed in benchmarks that memcached was slow for the first minute. ~350kngets/sec max, then it would jump up to millions/sec.nnif (it->time < current_time - ITEM_UPDATE_INTERVAL) {ncurrent_time starts at 2, which then underflows toward 4 billion, which isnlarger than it->time, so all fetches for the first minute require shufflingnthe LRU. Which happens under a global lock.nnThis probably goofed up all short-term benchmarks, and potentially slowed downnhigh traffic instances which were recently restarted.nnUnfortunately this means the tests no longer exercise item_update(), so somenmore work is necessary.n

use the right hashpower for the item_locks tableFor some reason I can't understand, I was accessing item_locks via the mainnhash table's power level, then modulus'ed to the number of item locks.nhashpower can change as the hash table grows, except it only ever changesnwhile no item locks are being held (via the item_global_lock synchronizationnbits). The item_locks hashpower is static for the duration.nnSo this isn't a safety issue, but instead just using the hash table wrongnand doing an extra modulus.nnAs an aside, this does improve benchmarks by a tiny bit.n

Avoid OOM errors when locked items stuck in tailIf a client fetches a few thousand keys, then does not ever read the socket,nthose keys will stay reflocked until the client disconnects or resumes. Ifnsome of those items are unpopular they can drop to the tail, causing allnwrites in the slab class to OOM.nnThis creates some relief by chucking the items back to the head.nnBig thanks to Jay Grizzard and other folks at Box for helping narrow thisndown.n

use item lock instead of global lock when hash expanding.

Pause all threads while swapping hash table.We used to hold a global lock around all modifications to the hash table.nnThen it was switched to wrapping hash table accesses in a global lock duringnhash table expansion, set by notifying each worker thread to change locknstyles. There was a bug here which causes trylocks to clobber, due to thenspecific item locks not being held during the global lock:nhttps://code.google.com/p/memcached/issues/detail?id=370nnThe patch previous to this one uses item locks during hash table expansion.nSince the item lock table is always smaller than the hash table, an item locknwill always cover both its new and old buckets.nnHowever, we still need to pause all threads during the pointer swap and setup.nThis patch pauses all background threads and worker threads, swaps the hashntable, then unpauses them.nnThis trades the (possibly significant) slowdown during the hash table copy,nwith a short total hang at the beginning of each expansion. As previously;nthose worried about consistent performance can presize the hash table withn`-o hashpower=n`n

Fix potential corruption for incr/decr of 0b itemsIt wasn't checking that the data was nonzero in size. Internally it usesnstrtoull, which ignores initial characters matched as spaces, then attempts tonparse the rest of the number.nnAn empty item has rn in the data section (min size 2), so if there'snparseable memory beyond the end of the data section in that chunk, possiblynfrom data previously occupying that space, it'll successfully delta it.nnIt won't corrupt memory, since it later tests for space to write the new valueninto (it->nbytes), and will then allocate a new item for the storage.n

cache_lock refactoringitem_lock() now protects accesses to item structures. cache_lock is just fornLRU and LRU stats. This patch removes cache_lock from a number of places it'snno longer needed.nnSome pre-existing bugs became obvious: flush_all, cachedump, and slabnreassignment's do_item_get short-circuit all need repairs.n

flush_all was not thread safe.Unfortunately if you disable CAS, all items set in the same second as anflush_all will immediately expire. This is the old (2006ish) behavior.nnHowever, if CAS is enabled (as is the default), it will still be more or lessnexact.nnThe locking issue is that if the LRU lock is held, you may not be able tonmodify an item if the item lock is also held. This means that some items maynnot be flushed if locking is done correctly.nnIn the current code, it could lead to corruption as an item could be lockednand in use while the expunging is happening.n
leave comment about stats cachedump locksIt's safe based on a technicality, which may not stay true for long.nnSame was true for stats sizes.n

Beginning work for LRU reworkPrimarily splitting cache_lock into a lock-per LRU, and making thenit->slab_clsid lookup indirect. cache_lock is now more or less gone.nnStats are still wrong. they need to internally summarize over eachnsub-class.n

first pass at LRU maintainer threadThe basics work, but tests still do not pass.nnA background thread wakes up once per second, or when signaled. It is signalednif a slab class gets an allocation request and has fewer than N chunks free.nnThe background thread shuffles LRU's: HOT, WARM, COLD. HOT is where new itemsnexist. HOT and WARM flow into COLD. Active items in COLD flow back to WARM.nEvictions are pulled from COLD.nnitem_update's no longer do anything (and need to be fixed to tick it->time).nItems are reshuffled within or around LRU's as they reach the bottom.nnRatios of HOT/WARM memory are hardcoded, as are the low/high watermarks.nThread is not fast enough right now, sets cannot block on it.n
reorg juggle routine, replace prints with statscode is clearer, and able to react a bit faster to required evictions.n

direct reclaim mode for evictionsOnly way to do eviction case fast enough is to inline it, sadly.nThis finally deletes the old item_alloc code now that I'm not intending onnreusing it.nnAlso removes the condition wakeup for the background thread. Instead runs on antimer, and meters its aggressiveness by how much shuffling is going on.nnAlso fixes a segfault in lru_pull_tail(), was unlinking `it` instead ofn`search`.n
fix itemstats to be combination of sub LRUseasier to reason, more tests pass.n

fix a few bugs and add more statswasn't passing total_chunks into the bg thread anymore, which causes all itemsnto flow to cold.nnalso re-added ability to see hot/warm/cold counts. NOEXP is missing untilnthat's implemented.n

LRU maintainer thread now fires LRU crawler... if available. Very simple starter heuristic for how often to run thencrawler.nnAt this point, this patch series should have a significant impact on hitnratio.n

compat mode.Enabling the new LRU routine requires starting with `-o lru_maintainer`.nnThis makes almost all of the tests pass, except refhang.t. Will need new testsnfor the LRU maintainer.nnSo far as I can tell it's still handling the refhang scenario, but in a morennatural way. Instead of flipping the items back to the top of the list, it'snunlinking them from the hash table and LRU. This completely removes them fromnthe problem, but it doesn't retry as many times to get them out of the way.nnA system with many stuck items next to each other could do a handful of OOM'snbefore clearing the backlog, but it won't keep running into them. The testnappears flaky even in 1.4.22; running with -vv causes it to fail in a funnynway.n

spinlocks never seem to help in benchmarksIf a thread is allowed to go to sleep, it can be woken up early as soon as thenlock is freed. If we spinlock, the scheduler can't help us and threads willnrandomly run out their timeslice until the thread actually holding the locknfinishes its work.nnIn my benchmarks killing the spinlock only makes things better.n

restore slab_automove=2 support and add testTest is a port of a golang test submitted by Scott Mansfield.nnThere used to be an angry birds mode to slabs_automove, which attempts tonforce a slab move from any slab into the one which just had an eviction.nThis is an imperfect but fast way of responding to shifts in memorynrequirements.nnThis change adds it back in plus a test which very quickly attempts to setndata in via noreply. This isn't the end of improvements here. This commit is anstarting point.n

slab mover rescues valid items with free chunksDuring a slab page move items are typically ejected regardless of theirnvalidity. Now, if an item is valid and free chunks are available in the samenslab class, copy the item over and replace it.nnIt's up to external systems to try to ensure free chunks are available beforenmoving a slab page. If there is no memory it will simply evict them as normal.nnAlso adds counters so we can finally tell how often these cases happen.n

properly shuffle page list after slab moveused to take the newest page of the page list and replace the oldest page withnit. so only the first page we move from a slab class will actually be old.ninstead, actually burn the slight CPU to shuffle all of the pointers down one.nNow we always chew the oldest page.n

first half of new slab automoverIf any slab classes have more than two pages worth of free chunks, attempt tonfree one page back to a global pool.nnCreate new concept of a slab page move destination of 0, which is a globalnpage pool. Pages can be re-assigned out of that pool during allocation.nnCombined with item rescuing from the previous patch, we can safely shufflenpages back to the reassignment pool as chunks free up naturally. This shouldnbe a safe default going forward. Users should be able to decide to free ornmove pages based on eviction pressure as well. This is coming up in anotherncommit.nnThis also fixes a calculation of the NOEXP LRU size, and completely removesnthe old slab automover thread. Slab automove decisions will now be part of thenlru maintainer thread.n
documentation for slab rebal updatessome new variables and change to the '1' mode. little sad nobody noticed I'dnaccidentally removed the '2' mode for a few versions.n
fix off by one in slab shufflingThanks Devon :)n

fix memory corruption in slab page moverIf item does not have ITEM_SLABBED bit, or ITEM_LINKED bit, logic was fallingnthrough, defaulting to MOVE_PASS. If an item has had storage allocated vianitem_alloc(), but haven't completed the data upload, it will sit in this mode.nWith MOVE_PASS for an item in this state, if no other items trip the busynre-scan of the page the mover will consider the page completely wiped evennwith the outstanding item.nnThe hilarious bit is I'd clearly thought this through: the top comment statesnthe if this, then this, or that... with the or that logic completelynmissing. Add one line of code and it survived a 5 hour torture test, wherenbefore it crashed after 30-60 minutes.nnLeaves some handy debug code #ifdef'ed out. Also moves the memset wipe on pagenmove completion to only happen if the page isn't being returned to the globalnpage pool, as the page allocator does a memset and chunk-split.nnThanks to Scott Mansfield for the initial information eventually leading tonthis discovery.n

mem_requested from stats slabs is now accurateDuring an item rescue, item size was being added to the slab class when thennew chunk requested, and then not removed again from the total if the item wasnsuccessfully rescued. Now just always remove from the total.n
call STATS_LOCK() less in slab mover.uses the slab_rebal struct to summarize stats, more occasionally grabbing thenglobal lock to fill them in, instead.n
tune automove to required 2.5 pages of free chunksif we're deciding to move pages right on the chunk boundary it's too easy toncause flapping.n

stop using slab class 255 for page moverclass 255 is now a legitimate class, used by the NOEXP LRU when thenexpirezero_does_not_evict flag is enabled. Instead, we now force a single bitnITEM_SLABBED when a chunk is returned to the slabber, andnITEM_SLABBED|ITEM_FETCHED means it's been cleared for a page move.nnitem_alloc overwrites the chunk's flags on set. The only weirdness wasnslab_free |='ing in the ITEM_SLABBED bit. I tracked that down to a commit inn2003 titled more debugging and can't come up with a good enough excuse fornpreserving an item's flags when it's been returned to the free memory pool. Sonnow we overload the flag meaning.n

split rebal_evictions into _nomem and _samepagegross oversight putting two conditions into the same variable. now can tell ifnwe're evicting because we're hitting the bottom of the free memory pool, or ifnwe keep trying to rescue items into the same page as the one being cleared.n

try harder to save itemspreviously the slab mover would evict items if the new chunk was within thenslab page being moved. now it will do an inline reclaim of the chunk and trynuntil it runs out of memory.n

fix over-inflation of total_mallocedmem_alloced was getting increased every time a page was assigned out of eithernmalloc or the global page pool. This means total_malloced will inflate forevernas pages are reused, and once limit_maxbytes is surpassed it will stopnattempting to malloc more memory.nnThe result is we would stop malloc'ing new memory too early if page reclaimnhappens before the whole thing fills. The test already caused this condition,nso adding the extra checks was trivial.n

'lru_crawler enable' blocks until readysingle CPU VM builders could fail:n - spawn LRU crawler thread.n - signal LRU crawler.n - LRU crawler thread now waits on condition.n - Crawler thread misses condition, sits forever.nnMight also want to move the stats.lru_crawler_running bit to be updated whennthe crawler thread picks up the work to do, somehow.n

make slab reassign tests more reliableon 32bit hardware with different pointer/slab class sizes, the tests wouldnfail. made a few adjustments to ensure reassign rescues happen and make itemsnnot be near the default slab class borders.nnThis makes the tests pass, but needs further improvements for reliability..nie: fill until evicts, count slab pages for reassignment/etc.n

initial logger code.Logs are written to per-thread buffers. A new background thread aggregates thenlogs, further processes them, then writes them to any watchers.nnLogs can have the time added to them, and all have a GID so they can be putnback into strict order.nnThis is an early preview. Code needs refactoring and a more complete set ofnoptions. All watchers are also stuck viewing the global feed of logs, even ifnthey asked for different data.nnAs of this commit there's no way to toggle the stderr watcher.n
manage logger watcher flags.very temporary user control. allows to watch either fetchers or evictions, butnnot both, and always with timestamps.n
switch from bit fields to bit manipulationcan't compare bit fields en-masse, which makes things too difficult.n

remove logger chunks, add individualized streamsStop doing a multi-reader circular buffer structure on top of a circularnbuffer. Also adds individualized streams based off of the central buffer.nnSadly this requires managing iovecs and dealing with partial writes into saidniovecs. That makes things very complicated. Since it's not clear to me how tonsimplify it too much (as of this writing), one of the next commits shouldnremove iovecs and instead give each watcher its own circular buffer. Thenparser thread will copy watched events into each buffer.nnThe above would only be slower for the case of many watchers watching the samenevent streams. Given all of the extra loops required for managing the iovecs,nand the more complicated syscall handling, it might even be the same speed tonmanage multiple buffers anyway.nnI completed this intermediary change since it simplifies the surrounding codenand was educational to fiddle with iovecs again.n

use one bipbuffer per watcher. remove iovec code.after the previous commit's exercise, this greatly simplifies the writingnprocess. The buffers are large but can be tuned with performance testing.nnLines are now rendered into scratch space, and if event flags (eflags) matchnfor a watcher, copy the bytes into that watcher's specific buffer.nnIn most realistic cases, watchers will be watching different streams ofninformation. While this does require a minimum of one memcpy instead ofndirectly writing into the bipbuf as before, it removes all of the loops andnmanagement of iovecs required for filtering events on the write-to-socket end.n

poll() smarter when full, print skipped countWhen lines are skipped to a watcher, a [skipped: n] is printed beforenresuming. Also polls full watcher directly once, and will wait until thenouter loop to re-poll.nnThink the routine can be simplified... it works so will leave it and revisitnlater.n
improve 'watch' command processing a littlemoves to its own function, respods OKrn to client, allows multiplenarguments for multiple flags. Needs more thought before adding sampling.n
some basic tests for the watcher.
some global stats for bg loggerfour obvious ones. have a handy place to do the summarization when the loggernwakes up for its run, avoiding the locks.n

Fix undefined behavior in vlen checkThe size check for vlen in process_get_command was relying onnundefined behavior (signed integer overflow) to check to seenif vlen was greater than 2^31-2. This made certain compilersn(such as clang 7.3.x) optimize out part of the conditional andnprevent memcache from erroring when the specified size wasnexactly 2^31-1, leading to an incorrect error message and a corendump. This patch does that overflow test in a not-undefined-behaviornway.nnFixes failure in issue_70.t test #4 on those platforms.n

Do LRU-bumps while already holding item lockitem_get() would hash, item_lock, fetch item.nconsumers which can bump the LRU would then call item_update(),nwhich would hash, item_lock, then update the item.nnGood performance bump by inlining the LRU bump when it's necessary.n

stop using atomics for item refcount managementwhen I first split the locks up further I had a trick where item_remove()ndid not require holding the associated item lock. If an item were to be freed,nit would then do the necessary work.;nnSince then, all calls to refcount_incr and refcount_decr only happen while thenitem is locked. This was mostly due to the slab mover being very tricky withnlocks. The atomic is no longer needed as the refcount is only ever checkednafter a lock to the item.nnCalling atomics is pretty expensive, especially in multicore/multisocketnscenarios. This yields a notable performance increase.n

test hit ratio fix for LRU maintainer modeunder higher loads, the LRU maintainer might not get to peek at a tail beforenan eviction is required, so active items at the tail can be pulled.nnThis attempts to address it in two ways: one, allow the LRU maintainer threadnto run even faster. Two, if you get a hit in cold, immediately move to warm.nThis also stops pulling from HOT/WARM during an eviction cycle.nnThis is a long-missing part of the algorithm which has a more optimized routenof per-worker-thread queues of moving items to warm. That should re-enablenno-shuffling-during gets. In this test mode, shuffling only happens in thenrelatively rare hits on cold. Hits on HOT/WARM are both shuffled by the LRUnmaintainer thread.n

NOEXP_LRU can now act as a transient LRUBeen resisting this for a long time due to how HOT operates. However it'snprobably a good way to relieve some pressure off the LRU crawler and do fewerncross-LRU juggles.nnThe NOEXP LRU can still function by simply setting the transient_ttl to 0n(handy!). This is a test so the variables haven't been renamed yet, andnthere's a perhaps temporary command for live-modification of the transientnthreshold.n

LRU maint test fix for second mysteryIf an LRU is too large, ACTIVE processing was elided on purpose. However it'snvery easy for even moderate write pressure to pass a large number of ACTIVEnitems into COLD. This combined with not removing items from COLD immediatelyn(fixed in another commit) could easily cause very active items to be evictednalong with inactive ones.nnWith the speedup of the processing thread (with some low-fruit still), itnshould be fine to quickly flip items in place.nnThis opens up a problem under extreme write pressure which overwhelms thenbackground thread, or extreme re-scanning of large numbers of items.nnIt might still be valuable to do pressure release or direct reclaim pulling ifnCOLD gets too large. Performance tests should be done to find the thresholdnand experiment.n

pull HOT tail if COLD+EVICT has no reclaimsThe previous method would always pull both HOT and WARM before attempting tonpull COLD for eviction. This isn't the greatest performance, but simplynattempting to evict from COLD makes the code difficult to test. It also has anbad effect if a ton of traffic comes in while the LRU maintainer has a highnsleep value, or sustained higher than the thread can keep up with.nnA good tradeoff is simple; pull HOT tail if COLD+EVICT causes no reclaims,nthen loop.nnTests now work again and should still be faster than old way in production.n

NOEXP_LRU is now TEMP_LRUConfident the other feature was never used; and if someone wants it, it's easynto restore by allowing exptime of 0 to go into TEMP_LRU.nnThis could possibly become a default, or at least recommended.n

LRU maintainer performance: per-class sleepEven if just one slab class is active, each wake of the LRU maintainernthread would pull the tail of all available LRU's in all available slabnclasses.nnWith this change they are independently scheduled, which should improventhroughput of the thread.n

move WARM_LRU requires two hits overallITEM_FETCHED and ITEM_ACTIVE are now tracked separately. This also ensuresnthese flags are added only when an item would normally be bumped (previouslynand INCR/DECR, failed store, etc could do it.nnThe original segmented LRU papers require two hits to be considered frequentlynaccessed. It's not completely clear if the initial cache miss counts as a hitnin the papers but increasing the frequency required to reach WARM still helps.n
Active items in HOT_LRU flow to WARM_LRUPreviously they would stay in HOT, which disagrees with the papers and is anwaste of space + contention on the HOT_LRU.n

autotuning for HOT/WARM LRU'sBy default 1/3rd of cache memory can go to HOT and WARM. I've noticed manynpeople's caches will shrink to 1/3rd, while others may have items sit idle innWARM for many times longer than the size of COLD.nnThis adds another factor for capping the size of each LRU; maximum idle ages.nIf items sit idle for an hour in HOT, they're a good candidate for COLD. Innthe new default WARM items will get twice the idle time of COLD for a chancento stay in WARM and get hit again.n

use LRU thread for COLD -> WARM bumpsPrevious tree fixed a problem; active items needed to be processed from thentail of COLD, which makes evictions harder without evicting active items.nnCOLD bumps were modified to be immediate (old style). This uses anper-worker-thread mostly-nonblocking queue that the LRU thread consumes fornCOLD bumps.nnIn most cases, hits to COLD are 1/10th or less than the other classes. On highnrates of access where the buffers fill, those items simply don't get theirnACTIVE bit set. If they get hit again with free space, they will be processednthen. This prevents regressions from high speed keyspace scans.n

Allow switching LRU algo's at runtimeIf LRU maintainer thread is started, this allows you to switch between flatnand segmented modes at runtime. The maintainer thread will drain HOT/WARMnLRU's if put into flat mode, and no new items should fill in.nnThis was much easier than expected...n

refactor chunk chaining for memory efficiencyMemory chunk chains would simply stitch multiple chunks of the highest slabnclass together. If your item was 17k and the chunk limit is 16k, the itemnwould use 32k of space instead of a bit over 17k.nnThis refactor simplifies the slab allocation path and pulls the allocation ofnchunks into the upload process. A large item gets a small chunk assigned asnan object header, rather than attempting to inline a slab chunk into a parentnchunk. It then gets chunks individually allocated and added into the chainnwhile the object uploads.nnThis solves a lot of issues:nn1) When assembling new, potentially very large items, we don't have to sit andnspin evicting objects all at once. If there are 20 16k chunks in the tail andnwe allocate a 1 meg item, the new item will evict one of those chunksninbetween each read, rather than trying to guess how many loops to run beforengiving up. Very large objects take time to read from the socket anyway.nn2) Simplifies code around the initial chunk. Originally embedding data intonthe top chunk and embedding data at the same time required a good amount ofnfiddling. (Though this might flip back to embedding the initial chunk if I cannclean it up a bit more).nn3) Pulling chunks individually means the slabber code can be flatened to notnthink about chunks aside from freeing them, which culled a lot of code andnremoved branches from a hot path.nn4) The size of the final chunk is naturally set to the remaining about ofnbytes that need to be stored, which means chunks from another slab class cannbe pulled to cap off a large item, reducing memory overhead.n

fix ordering issue in conn dispatchvery old race condition: push to queue, write to signal pipe. with extstore,nhammering a secondary item type into the queue could occasionally swap thenitem with the type it represented.nnnow differentiate on the type, and the character signifies either to pull annitem or do something else entirely.n

Sleep more aggressively in some threadsThe logger and lru maintainer threads both adjust how long they sleepnbased on how busy they are. This adjustment should be exponential, tonmore quickly adjust to workloads.nnThe logger thread in particular would only adjust 50 microseconds at antime, and was capped at 100 milliseconds of sleep, causing manynunnecessary wakeups on an otherwise idle dev machine. Adjust this cap ton1 second.n

Add drop_privileges() for LinuxImplement an aggressive version of drop_privileges(). Additionally addnsimilar initialization function for threads drop_worker_privileges().nnThis version is similar to Solaris one and prohibits memcached fromnmaking any not approved syscalls. Current list narrows down the allowedncalls to socket sends/recvs, accept, epoll handling, futex (andndependencies - mmap), getrusage (for stats), and signal / exitnhandling.nnAny incorrect behaviour will result in EACCES returned. This should benrestricted further to KILL in the future (after more testing).nnThe feature is only tested for i386 and x86_64. It depends on bpfnfilters and seccomp enabled in the kernel. It also requires libsecompnfor abstraction to seccomp filters. All are available since Linux 3.5.nnSeccomp filtering can be enabled at compile time with --enable-seccomp.nnIn case of local customisations which require more rights, memcachednallows disabling drop_privileges() with -o no_drop_privileges atnstartup.nnTests have to run with -o relaxed_privileges, since they requirendisk access after the tests complete. This adds a few allowed syscalls,nbut does not disable the protection system completely.n

extstore: fix crash while moving extstore chunksITEM_LINKED was still set on the objects being written to disk. limit crawls for metadumperLRU crawler metadumper is used for getting snapshot-y looks at the LRU's.nSince there's no default limit, it'll get any new items added or bumped sincenthe roll started.nnwith this change it limits the number of items dumped to the number thatnexisted in that LRU when the roll was kicked off. You still end up with annapproximation, but not a terrible one:nn- items bumped after the crawler passes them likely won't be revisitedn- items bumped before the crawler passes them will likely be visited towardn  the end, or mixed with new items.n- deletes are somewhere in the middle.n

remove redundant counter/lock from hash tablecurr_items tracks how many items are linked in the hash table. internally tonthe hash table, hash_items tracked how many items were in the hash table.nnon every insert/delete, hash_items had to be locked and checked to see if thntable should be expanded. rip that all out, and call a check with thenonce-per-second clock event to check for hash table expansion.nnthis actually ends up fixing an obscure bug: if you burst a bunch of setsnthen stop, the hash table won't attempt to expand a second time until thennext insert. with this change, every second the hash table has a chance ofnexpanding again.n

systemd instancing support & rpm build improvementsThe major things this does are adding systemd support to the rpm .specnfile, and adding systemd instancing support. This means that it isnpossible to run multiple memcached instances without having to donany additional configuration or hack on init scripts.nnTo use:nsystemctl start memcached@11211 memcached@11311 memcached@11411nnsysconfig files at /etc/sysconfig/memcached.<port> will be read asnappropriate, to allow differing configurations per-port. Defaultsnwill be read from /etc/sysconfig/memcached before the port-specificnsettings are read.nnYou can also still start memcached the standard way just by doingnsystemctl start memcached. This will read /etc/sysconfig/memcachednand nothing else.nnThe enhanced security lines in the systemd unit file will be commentednout on systems where we know systemd isn't knew enough (fedora < 26 andnRedhat/CentOS 7), and enabled on other systems.nnThere are two versions of the .service file included, one for standardnmemcached invocations and one for instanced invocations. The two arenvery similar, but not identical. Ideally, we'd only have one versionnin the source tree and we'd massage it with sed or somesuch during thenrpm build, but couldn't think of a super clean way to do that, so errednon the side of simplicity.nnA decent amount of spec file work was needed to enable this functionality.nIn the process, I also cleaned up several additional aspects of the specnfile (like using %{name} in places where it was appropriate). I alsoncommented out the automatic restart in the %postun section, for two mainnreasons:n1. The try-restart for instanced memcached will produce an error ifninstanced memcached isn't in use, which is probably quite confusing tonpeople who aren't using that functionality and are just trying to updatentheir package. (There's workarounds for this, but I try to keep pre/postnscripts as simple as humanly possible)nn2. Automatic restarts on updates means the cache gets flushed, whichnmeans you can no longer safely use large-scale management tools (likenpuppet or chef) to roll out new versions, at least not without a lotnof planning first. Not automatically dumping someone's caches feelsnsafer, here.n

Replace event_init() with new API if detect newer versionIf we detect libevent version >= 2.0.2-alpha, change to usenevent_base_new_with_config() instead of obsolete event_init() for creating newnevent base. Set config flag to EVENT_BASE_FLAG_NOLOCK to avoid lock/unlocknaround every libevent operation.nnFor newer version of libevent, the event_init() API is deprecated and isntotally unsafe for multithreaded use. By using the new API, we can explicitlyndisable/enable locking on the event_base.n

disable UDP port by defaultAs reported, UDP amplification attacks have started to use insecureninternet-exposed memcached instances. UDP used to be a lot more popular as antransport for memcached many years ago, but I'm not aware of many recentnusers.nnTen years ago, the TCP connection overhead from many clients was relativelynhigh (dozens or hundreds per client server), but these days many clients arenbatched, or user fewer processes, or simply anre't worried about it.nnWhile changing the default to listen on localhost only would also help, thentrue culprit is UDP. There are many more use cases for using memcached overnthe network than there are for using the UDP protocol.n

Support seccomp on muslMusl-based distributions like Alpine didn't work with seccomp profilenenabled. This was due to musl using different syscalls than glibc undernthe cover.nn- writev/readv and epoll_pwait have been allowedn- specific ioctl has been allowed to enableprinting the error/exitn  messagen- brk has been allowed at runtimen- worker writes to stderr have been allowed (this was also broken onn  glibc)n

Enforce seccomp policyInstead of denying access when a forbidden syscall is triggered, killnthe whole process.nnThis is good because it prevents silent failures when running intonissues with new/different libc implementations. This is also good,nbecause failures to follow the policy causes an immediate, loud KILL.n

Drop supplementary groups in addition to setgidWhen launching as root, we drop permissions to run as a specificnuser, however the way this is done fails to drop supplementaryngroups from the process.nnOn many systems, the root user is a member of many groups used tonguard important system files. If we neglect to drop these groupsnit's still possible for a compromised memcached instance to accessncritical system files as though it were running with root levelnpermissions.nnOn any given system `grep root /etc/group` will reveal all thengroups root is a member of, and memcached will have access tonany file these groups are authorized for, in spite of our attemptsnto drop this access.nnIt's possible to test if a given memcached instance is affected bynthis and running with elevated permissions by checking the respectivenline in procfs: `grep Groups /proc/$pid/status`nnIf any groups are listed, memcached would have access to everythingnthe listed groups have access to. After this patch no groups willnbe listed and memcached will be locked down properly.n

fix deadlock during hash table expansionThe slab rebalancer was paused after the LRU maintainer thread during hashntable expansion. This was mostly fine, except in one case.nnIf an item is in the COLD LRU when it gets hit, it gets assigned an ACTIVEnbitflag and queued for an asynchronous bump. If the item already has annACTIVE bit, it does not queue a second time. Items in other LRU's are bumpednwhen they hit the tail, but COLD items have to bump relatively soon to avoidnaccidentally evicting recently active items while under memory pressure.nnItems queued for async bumps have an extra refcount.nnThe slab page mover cannot move a page until all memory within the page isncleared and freed. If it runs into an item which is stuck, it will try tondelete it, then wait for all of its references to be removed.nnHowever, if an item is in the bump queue when the LRU thread is stopped,nand the slab page mover is moving the page a queued item happens to be in,nthe refcount will never drop to zero as the bump will never happen.nnThe page mover has no mechanism for giving up partway through, so it loopsnforever. For most use cases, this degrades the instance but doesn't actuallynbreak much:nn- The COLD LRU's will eventually drain to zero.n- Allocations will all become direct reclaims, which force items into COLDn  and then evicts them.n- This will degrade the LRU algorithm and some performance, but if then  instance usage isn't very high most users may never notice.n- Normally, page moving is rare enough and hash table expansion is raren  enough that it's an unlikely race.nnHowever, with extstore, page moves tend to happen a lot more frequently.nAlso, items are only ever written to extstore from the COLD LRU's, so if theynempty the process will stop. This makes the race more likely to happen andnthe effects are more obvious.nnThe fix is to simply pause the page mover before the LRU thread. The LRUnthread does call the page mover, but it is via trylock() since it normallynexpects to progress even if the page mover is busy. The pause of the pagenmover won't succeed until it fully completes the current page, so it shouldnthen be clear to pause the LRU thread.nnFurther improvements could be made by allowing the page mover to bail after Nnunsuccessful loops. I am also considering removing the async LRU bumpnprocess, and letting the LRU crawler handle that instead.nnMuch thanks to Shashi and Sridhar from Netflix for all of their help inntracking down this bug!n

Fix segfault: Prevent calling sasl_server_step before sasl_server_startIf sasl_server_step is called on a sasl_conn which has not hadnsasl_server_start called on it, it will segfault from readingnuninitialized memory.nnMemcached currently calls sasl_server_start when the client sendsnthe PROTOCOL_BINARY_CMD_SASL_AUTH command and sasl_server_step whennthe client sends the PROTOCOL_BINARY_CMD_SASL_STEP command. So if thenclient sends SASL_STEP before SASL_AUTH, the server segfaults.nnFor well-behaved clients, this case never happens; but for thenjava-memcached-client, when configured with an incorrect password,nit happens very frequently. This is likely because the client handlesnauth on a background thread and the socket may be swapped out in thenmiddle of authentication. support transparent hugepages on LinuxLinux has supported transparent huge pages on Linux for quite some time.nMemory regions can be marked for conversion to huge pages with madvise.nAlternatively, Users can have the system default to using huge pages fornall memory regions when applicable, i.e. when the mapped region is largenenough, the properly aligned pages will be converted.nnUsing either method, we would preallocate memory for the cache withnproper alignment, and call madvise on it. Whether the memory regionnactually gets converted to hugepages ultimately depends on the settingnof /sys/kernel/mm/transparent_hugepage/enabled. The existence of thisnfile is also checked to see if transparent huge pages support is compiledninto the kernel.nnIf any step of the preallocation fails, we simply fallback to standardnallocation, without even preallocating slabs, as they would not haventhe proper alignment or settings anyway.n

split storage writer into its own threadtrying out a simplified slab class backoff algorithm. The LRU maintainernindividually schedules slab classes by time, which leads to multiple wakeupsnin a steady state as they get out of sync. This algorithm more simply skipsnthat class more often each time it runs the main loop, using a singlenscheduled sleep instead.nnif it goes to sleep for a long time, it also reduces the backoff for allnclasses. if we're barely awake it should be fine to poke everything.n

expand NEED_ALIGN for chunked itemssome whackarse ARM platforms on specific glibc/gcc (new?) versions tripnSIGBUS while reading the header chunk for a split item.nnthe header chunk is unfortunate magic: It lives in ITEM_data() at a randomnoffset, is zero sized, and only exists to simplify code around finding thenorignial slab class, and linking/relinking subchunks to an item.nnthere's no fix to this which isn't a lot of code. I need to refactor chunkednitems, and attempted to do so, but couldn't come up with something I likednquickly enough.nnThis change pads the first chunk if alignment is necessary, which wastesnbytes and a little CPU, but I'm not going to worry a ton for these obscurenplatforms.nnthis works with rebalancing because in the case of ITEM_CHUNKED header, itntreats the item size as the size of the class it resides in, and memcpy's thenitem during recovery.nnall other cases were changes from ITEM_data to a new ITEM_schunk() inlinenfunction that is created when NEED_ALIGN is set, else it's equal to ITEM_datanstill.n

move mem_requested from slabs.c to items.cmem_requested is an oddball counter: it's the total number of bytesnactually requested from the slab's caller. It's mainly used for anstats counter, alerting the user that the slab factor may not benefficient if the gap between total_chunks * chunk_size - mem_requestednis large.nnHowever, since chunked items were added it's _also_ used to help thenLRU balance itself. The total number of bytes used in the class vs thentotal number of bytes in a sub-LRU is used to judge whether to movenitems between sub-LRU's.nnThis is a layer violation; forcing slabs.c to know more about how itemsnwork, as well as EXTSTORE for calculating item sizes from headers.nFurther, it turns out it wasn't necessary for item allocation: if wenneed to evict an item we _always_ pull from COLD_LRU or force a movenfrom HOT_LRU. So the total doesn't matter.nnThe total does matter in the LRU maintainer background thread. However,nthis thread caches mem_requested to avoid hitting the slab lock toonfrequently. Since sizes_bytes[] within items.c is generally redundantnwith mem_requested, we now total sizes_bytes[] from each sub-LRU beforenstarting a batch of LRU juggles.nnThis simplifies the code a bit, reduces the layer violations in slabs.cnslightly, and actually speeds up some hot paths as a number of branchesnand operations are removed completely.nnThis also fixes an issue I was having with the restartable memorynbranch :) recalculating p->requested and keeping a clean API is painfulnand slow.nnNOTE: This will vary a bit compared to what mem_requested originallyndid, mostly for large chunked items.nnFor items which fit inside a single slab chunk, the stat is identical.nHowever, items constructed by chaining chunks will have a single largennbytes value and end up in the highest slab class. Chunked items cannbe capped with chunks from smaller slab classes; you will seenutilization of chunks but not an increase in mem_requested for them.nnI'm still thinking this through but this is probably acceptable. Largenchunked items should be accounted for separately, perhaps with some newncounters so they can be discounted from normal calculations.n

Make memcached setgroups failure non-fatalA call to setgroups can fail on Linux if the user lacks cap_setgid or if setgroups has been disallowed in a user namespace. The latter happens when the namespace has no GID map or if /proc/pid/setgroups has been changed to deny. Treating this failure as fatal means that memcached cannot start in a bazel fakeroot. Ignoring failure seems harmless.n

meta text protocol commands- we get asked a lot to provide a metaget command, for various usesn(debugging, etc)n- we also get asked for random one-off commands for various use cases.n- I really hate both of these situations and have been wanting tonexperiment with a slight tuning of how get commands work for a longntime.nnAssuming that if I offer a metaget command which gives people theninformation they're curious about in an inefficient format, plus datanthey don't need, we'll just end up with a slow command withncompatibility issues. No matter how you wrap warnings around a command,npeople will put it into production under high load. Then I'm stuck withnit forever.nnBehold, the meta commands!nnSee doc/protocol.txt and the wiki for a full explanation and examples.nnThe intent of the meta commands is to support any features the binarynprotocol had over the text protocol. Though this is missing somencommands still, it is close and surpasses the binary protocol in manynways.n

Keep last access time up to date in SLRU modeThe last access time used to only update once per minute to avoidnexcess bumping on hot items.
